The solution uses the method of descent on the largest element of $S$. 
We first establish that for any prime $p \in S$, there are at most two valid neighbors $q \in S$ with $q < p$. This follows from analyzing the equation $4pq = (2x+1)^2 - (4k-1)$ modulo $p$.
Since in any valid cyclic arrangement the largest element $m = \max S$ must have two neighbors and both must be smaller than $m$, these neighbors are uniquely determined as the set of all valid candidates smaller than $m$.
This implies that the set of edges in the cycle is uniquely determined by $S$. Since the edge set of a Hamiltonian cycle determines the cycle up to rotation and reflection, the result follows.

