The problem asks to prove the uniqueness (up to rotation and reflection) of a Hamiltonian cycle on a set of odd primes $S$ with a specific adjacency condition. The key number-theoretic insight is that for any prime $p \in S$, and any $q \in S$ with $q < p$ such that they are neighbors, $q$ must be of the form $(x^2+x+k)/p$ where $x < p$ is a root of $X^2+X+k \equiv 0 \pmod p$. Since a quadratic has at most 2 roots modulo a prime, there are at most 2 such neighbors $q < p$.
