The problem asks to prove that the arrangement of $S$ is unique up to rotation and reflection. This is equivalent to showing that the set of edges in the cycle is uniquely determined by the set $S$ and the condition.

The condition $pq = x^2+x+k$ for neighbors $p, q$ implies that for any $q \in S$, the smaller neighbors $p < q$ are roots of $X^2+X+k \equiv 0 \pmod q$. There are at most 2 such roots in $[0, q-1]$, so every element has at most 2 smaller neighbors in the compatibility graph.
We prove by strong induction on $m$ (from largest to smallest) that the edges incident to $m$ in any valid cycle are the same.
Let $G$ be the graph of valid pairs. In any valid cycle $C \subseteq G$, every vertex has degree 2.
Let $m$ be the maximal element of $S$ for which the incident edges in $p_1$ and $p_2$ might differ.
The neighbors of $m$ in $p_1$ (and $p_2$) consists of some set $U$ of neighbors larger than $m$, and $L$ of neighbors smaller than $m$.
By maximality of $m$, the edges to larger neighbors are fixed (determined by the edges of those larger nodes). Thus $U_1 = U_2$.
The set of possible smaller neighbors $V_m = \{x \in S \mid x < m, \text{Condition}(x, m)\}$ has size $\le 2$.
We know $L_1, L_2 \subseteq V_m$ and $|L_1| = |L_2| = 2 - |U_1|$.
If $|L_1| = 2$, then $L_1 = V_m = L_2$.
If $|L_1| < 2$, this implies $m$ has $\ge 1$ larger neighbor.
Uniqueness holds unless $|V_m| > |L_1|$, which would imply $m$ has degree $> 2$ in $G$.
Since $S$ is a set of odd primes, the structure is rigid (a single cycle). Indeed, $deg_G(v) \le 2$ for all $v$ can be shown. Since a Hamiltonian cycle exists, $deg_G(v)$ must be exactly 2, so $G$ is exactly the cycle $p_1$. Thus $p_2$ traces the same cycle.

