The proof relies on the fact that for any prime $p \in S$, there are at most two primes $q \in S$ with $q < p$ such that the condition holds. This implies that if we orient the edges of any valid configuration from larger to smaller primes, every vertex has out-degree at most 2. Since any Hamiltonian cycle has degree 2 at every vertex, we can show that the set of edges is uniquely determined by peeling off the vertices from largest to smallest. Specifically, if two valid edge sets $E_1$ and $E_2$ differed, the largest vertex $p$ where they differ would have the same edges to larger neighbors but different edges to smaller neighbors. This would force a discrepancy in the number of smaller neighbors for some $q < p$, creating an infinite descent of differences, which is impossible in a finite set.

