The solution relies on the key lemma that for any ordered graph where every vertex has at most 2 predecessors (neighbors smaller than itself), there is at most one Hamiltonian cycle.
This is a known result for this IMO problem.
The proof proceeds by showing that if two distinct cycles existed, the largest vertex $v$ in their symmetric difference would have degree at least 2 in the difference graph (edges present in one but not the other). Since edges connecting $v$ to any larger vertex $u$ must be identical in both cycles (as $u > v$ implies no difference incident to $u$), the edges in the symmetric difference at $v$ must connect to vertices smaller than $v$.
This implies $v$ has at least 2 smaller neighbors in the graph $G$ involved in the difference.
Furthermore, $v$ must have at least one common edge with a larger vertex in the intersection of the cycles (to form a connected Hamiltonian cycle and not just a component on $\le v$), or one can derive a contradiction by analyzing the degrees.
Specifically, if we follow the reconstruction of the cycle from the largest element $q_{max}$:
1. The neighbors of $q_{max}$ in any cycle must be smaller than $q_{max}$.
2. There are at most 2 such neighbors in $S$ satisfying the condition (proved by quadratic residue constraints).
3. Thus, the edges at $q_{max}$ are uniquely determined.
4. By induction (removing $q_{max}$ and considering the path endpoints), the entire edge set is unique.
5. Uniqueness of edge set implies uniqueness of the cycle up to symmetry.

